Date:         Fri, 2 Feb 1996 09:12:36 -0800
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Ray Davis <raydavis@BEST.COM>
Subject:      Re: poetics of the quotidian
 
It was a great and unanticipated relief for me to find Silliman's poetry
written on a bus about riding a bus. Hannah Weiner is the only "mystical"
poet I know of whose spirit voices tell her to sit up straight, stop being
such a loser, etc.
 
In fact, if we define "language poetry" as the poets I found starting with
_In the American Tree_, I'd say that the first big rush for me was
precisely that all the writers, no matter what their differences, had found
ways to avoid that horrible "I am a sensitive artist looking for sensitive
situations" tone we're all so familiar with from mainstream poetries, thus
allowing a little real life to creep back in. Or rather a wide range of
real lives.
 
Ray
