I went to a little talk the other day at which Marjorie chatted about
some of this stuff, with reference to what I think must be the intro. of
the MS in question, which makes the book look worth reading--it's about
Wittgenstein and stuff, subTI "...the Strangeness of the Ordinary", but
of course she'll tell more and better.
Anyway I'm wondering (and she probably goes into this, or could) whether
perhaps the term "poetics of the quotidian" could be narrowed to
_language_ of the quotidian, and whether that might generate some better
discussion; when we ask ?'s w/such enormous terms as "poetics" we know
we're heade to murky territory in the first place, and in the second
place we're really not saying much anyway.  Enough about themes, etc.!
What's distinct, not about some Mode of L poetry, but about its uses and
abuses of its own materiality?
 
Hoipe this has been suitably time-consuming for all,  Ryan
 
