Date:         Tue, 6 Feb 1996 15:20:11 -0600
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Charles Alexander <chax@MTN.ORG>
Subject:      Re: We all break for laokoon
 
There's a sculpture garden in St. Paul with poetry engraved on walkways and
on sculpture, poems by poets from various local cultures. There's a bridge
by Siah Armijani a few years old (I'm not exactly sure just how old) in
Minneapolis from the Walker Art Center Sculpture Garden to Loring Park which
includes a text by John Ashbery. There's language all over art a la Jenny
Holzer, Barbara Kruger, and many more, some of these works being sculpture,
some prints, more rarely (but sometimes) paintings. The book arts has an
entire area of activity that is properly perceived as language sculpture or
sculpture with language.
 
 
>anybody know of any ties between poetry and sculpture lately?
>or poetry and painting, for that matter?
>poetry and rodeo?
>poetry and dance, poetry and music, poetry and tv, these seem kind of
>available now in a way that poetry and film, poetry and dogsledding, poetry
>and critique may be less available than they used to be..
>
>Jordan
>
>
