Date:         Mon, 12 Feb 1996 18:34:30 -0800
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Ryan Knighton <knighton@SFU.CA>
Subject:      Re: writing the body
In-Reply-To:  <v01520d01ad452e56633f@[205.134.228.61]> from "Kevin Killian" at
              Feb 12, 96 05:53:53 pm
 
I'm not sure, as I haven't been around much as of late, if this strain
is strictly reserved for a feminist angle or application. However, I
would like to point out that I too find Maria's phrasing radically
different from Cix's, and, in some respects more interesting (maybe
because I have access to it then).  "Selected Organs", Nichol's
"autoBIOgraphy", is a fine example of the difference: writing the body
as writing, the body as narrative (life)line.  Re-membering (not
intending a phallic twist).  I think it opens the forum of discussion
to other politics than those Cix circumnavigates--I should say, other
politics that JUST those.  So if I might pose a question, any thoughts
on the relationship between body and memory and the writing of?
(I keep seeing a tattoo I know of for some reason)
 
Back and tattooing the monitor,
Ryan
