From Ron's post:
 
Good news for teachers, not so good for writers.... Less good still for
anthologists and publishers.
 
 
The U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit ruled that James M.
Smith, owner of Michigan Document Services, was protected by the "fair use"
provisions of copyright law and had not infringed on the copyrights of
the three publishers that sued him in 1992.
____________
 
A friend in Houghton Mifflin's legal department tells me that Mr. Smith had
mailed a couple of checks for an amount that he estimated to be fair when his
case wasn't going so well.  I wonder if he'll want them back.
 
