Date:         Wed, 21 Feb 1996 10:18:47 -0500
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         Jim Pangborn <V072GDXG@UBVMS.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Organization: University at Buffalo
Subject:      Re: Charles Alexander, John Milton, & 24 Hours of Democracy
 
"Christopher L. Filkins" <filch@POBOX.COM> promises
 
> (a brownie to anyone who can tell me what chronotope means and where it
> comes from)
 
The term was coined by M. M. Bakhtin, also spelt Baxtin, to refer to the
way matters of time and space interrelate in novelistic representations--
their "intrinsic connectedness."  The concept functions to produce
"formally constitutive categor[ies] of literature," meaning that he uses
it to generate categories of novels in a manner that points up formal
structures but doesn't get too airily abstract or ahistorical about it.
It can be a way, for example, of summing up and explaining formal
differences between _Joseph Andrews_, a "road novel," and _The Castle of
Otranto_, etc.
 
See Bakhtin's _The Dialogic Imagination_, U Texas P 1981.
 
--JimP
