Date:         Wed, 21 Feb 1996 09:54:54 -0800
Reply-To:     UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
Sender:       UB Poetics discussion group <POETICS@UBVM.CC.BUFFALO.EDU>
From:         "Christopher J. Beach" <cjbeach@BENFRANKLIN.HNET.UCI.EDU>
Subject:      Re: legacies
In-Reply-To:  <Pine.3.89.9602210943.A26804-0100000@gwis2.circ.gwu.edu>
 
Dear Mark:
 
Thanks for the very interesting reply to my query.  As one who has
thought quite long and hard about questions of poetic influence (altho
not a poet myself), I appreciate your own thinking about these issues.
As to the question of defining who's a language poet and who's not, I ask
it only in the context of getting straight the M-poets' (to me) overly
systematic rejection of Language, without a clear definition of exactly what that
means.  (Or, even more vaguely, the rejection of the "contemporary
avant-garde," a term that covers a lot of ground).
 
I'm not sure if I can mount a good defense of Hejinian as a
"transcendental" poet, but I am about to teach her in my seminar,
so I should have a better idea after that.  I think Daly is right about
Howe as well.  "Transcendental" does not have to mean unrigorous or
ideologically naive.  I mean transcendental in the sense of making space
for the irrational, for the "poetic," whatever that is.  I'm not sure if
it is exactly "religious," but "meditational," perhaps?
 
C Beach
 
 
 
