In some ways, Spicer seems the reluctant inheritor of Keats' "negative
capability" with an attitude. Where the "penetralium of the mystery"
is simply what Robin Blaser, in that beautiful essay on Olson's
violets, calls "the depth of the world". But with Spicer always
grotesquely and painfully funny. God as a big white baseball.
 
Mike
mboughn@epas.utoronto.ca
