Ron--I'm not sure exactly what "Calvinistic atheism" would be, but I do
think that Spicer was working both within and against a transcendental
tradition, both back thru poets like Lorca and Rilke, and in dialogue
with Duncan and Blaser.  The meditative in Spicer would have to do with
the poetic process itself, the process of "dictation"--having the
furniture in the room and waiting for the signal from outside (from Mars or
wherever) to come in and write the poem.
 
C Beach
 
